\begin{abstract}
This manuscript develops a four-dimensional fast-slow dynamical system for the stable boundary layer (SBL) using Geometric Singular Perturbation Theory (GSPT). The model couples fast turbulent kinetic energy evolution with slow atmospheric rotational and surface thermodynamic variables and is analyzed through its algebraic constraint geometry and reduced-layer decomposition. We show how compact normally hyperbolic subsets of the constraint set organize the slow dynamics. Rather than an interior saddle-node collapse, turbulence collapse occurs through termination of the attracting active branch at the physical admissibility boundary, where the singular perturbation description ceases to apply. The governing equations reproduce Blackadar-type inertial oscillations without prescribing them phenomenologically. The framework provides a geometric interpretation of SBL regime transitions across parameter regimes; {{dataset}} is used here as the reference parameter set for generated diagnostics and baseline tables.
\end{abstract}
